{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3536786,"name":"Josh","username":"AegisNova","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/aegisnova/{size}/265035_2.png","created_at":"2025-02-22T23:41:55.637Z","cooked":"

So generally, when you’re 3D printing something like a snap on clip, do you go for exact sizing, slightly smaller, or slightly larger?

I tried using the Clippard tanks and their clips for reference, but on Onshape, the clips register 2.31 inches inside diameter, but the tank is 2.5 inches in diameter.

I’m going for a clip that will go on a pneumatic cylinder housing, so it has a generally square shape with a decent amount of curves. So I was wondering if this peculiar shape will affect whether I need to make the print larger or smaller.

Any input is greatly appreciated, so thanks in advance!

There is a lot of Variables at play here. The width and destiny of the plastic clip, the printing orientation, the type of filament, and the accuracy of your printer all matter here. This type of thing usually takes some trial and error. I would start by making it ever so slightly smaller and go from there. It also helps to use something like PETG filament other than PLA filament, as PLA likes to snap without bending much.

Ok. Here’s what I can tell you:

  • We are using ABS for the filament
  • Our printers are StrataSys’s so I believe they’re pretty accurate
  • And they’re going to be used as a “wedge” for centering the cage on our climber.

I’ve attached pictures down below on how I’d like it to sit, but It’s all hypothetical

Screenshot 2025-02-22 190401628×667 54.7 KB

I decided to only make the curves smaller, but tried making the other edges slightly larger

I don’t have a lot of experience on compliant part design, so all I can do is ask: Are you sure a snap-on part is really needed here?

From what I understand, this is not something you will need to remove too often, right? If it’s possible, I would suggest designing either something that slides in from one of the ends of the housing, or making your piece in two halves and bolting them together.

If you are dead set on making snap-on clips, though, my inexperienced guess would be that you should try sticking with the outermost geometry. These little details really don’t seem like they would flex in and out of place very easily:

I don’t particularly know either. I like the bolt together idea, which I might adopt. But I don’t particularly know how well a snap on would work. I was told to cook up an idea for a snap on sort of wedge. And it doesn’t help that the cylinder isn’t symmetric.

Although, sliding in and out would be good, it’d require taking the caps off the end on the cylinder, which is securely fastened to our robot with rivets, bolts, and tight enough spacing as is.

Thanks for the input, but I should definitely discuss more in detail with my crew.

Ah I see what you’re trying to do now.

I Don’t think a snap fit is best for this kind of situation. It could be quite easily knocked straight off by the cage. A 2-piece design like the previous post mentioned would probably be a lot easier and stronger.

@Lyinlyon @predobrega

Last question for you folk.

If I’m going to push for a two piece, how much do you think I should mess with the curves?

Because realistically I don’t think the curves won’t do too much besides probably help with simple alignment.

I think my suggestion would still be to stick mostly with the outer geometry. It’s good to have something to help with alignment, but messing with the little details just seems like asking for something to not fit.
